INSERT INTO public.stories (title, description, image, author_name, location) VALUES

('From Doorstep Seller to Digital Entrepreneur',
'I used to walk 8 kilometers every morning to sell my block-printed cotton dupattas at the weekly haat in Sanganer. My feet ached, my earnings barely covered the dye costs, and middlemen took nearly 40% of every sale. When my daughter showed me EmpowerHer on her mobile phone, I did not believe a screen could change my life. But within three months of listing my products online, I received my first order from Bangalore — someone who had never visited Rajasthan, buying directly from me. Today I work from home, train six neighborhood women in block printing, and have shipped to buyers across fourteen cities. My daughter no longer needs to worry about my future.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1594736797933-d0501ba2fe65?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Dropadi Saini', 'Sanganer, Rajasthan'),

('Bamboo Craft Saved My Family''s Heritage',
'When my husband passed away in 2018, I was left with three children and a workshop full of bamboo — the only skill I had learned from my father. Bamboo weaving is considered low-value work in our district. Buyers offered me ₹30 for baskets that took half a day to make. I almost quit and migrated to the city for domestic work. A field officer from a local NGO introduced me to EmpowerHer. They connected me with an artisan collective and helped me photograph my work properly. I listed my bamboo planters, wall decor, and storage baskets. Within six months, my income tripled. Now I run a self-help group of nineteen women, and we have a waiting list for our handcrafted bamboo furniture.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558618666-fcd25c85cd64?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Champa Barua', 'Kokrajhar, Assam'),

('How I Built a Soap Business in My Kitchen',
'I learned cold-process soap making from a YouTube video during lockdown. My first batch was a disaster — the oils separated and it smelled of nothing. But I kept trying. By my fifth batch, I had turmeric-neem bars that my neighbors were begging to buy. I had no money for a shop, no contacts to reach buyers beyond my village. EmpowerHer gave me the platform and an NGO partner gave me a micro-loan of ₹15,000 for raw materials. Today, my brand Mitti Sugandhit has over 200 repeat customers, three product lines — herbal soaps, hair oils, and lip balms — and I have paid back my loan in full. I did all of this without leaving my home in Wardha.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1556228578-8c89e6adf883?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Savita Wankhede', 'Wardha, Maharashtra'),

('Madhubani Paintings Found Global Buyers',
'My grandmother painted Madhubani on mud walls for festivals — it was never meant to be sold. When I started painting on paper and canvas, the village elders said it was a waste of time. I could not find buyers willing to pay more than ₹100 for a painting that took three days. Through EmpowerHer, I connected with a funding partner who printed my work as greeting cards and notebooks. The wall art went viral on social media. An export buyer from Germany placed an order for 200 pieces. That single order changed everything. I now run a studio where I teach twelve young women the art form, and together we have preserved a tradition that almost died with our grandmothers.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1572375992501-4b0892d50c69?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Kamla Devi Jha', 'Madhubani, Bihar'),

('Spices from My Farm to Your Kitchen',
'We grow turmeric, red chili, coriander, and fenugreek on our three-acre family farm in Guntur. For twenty years, we sold everything to a single trader who set the price. We had no bargaining power and no idea who our real customers were. My youngest son helped me photograph our spices and list them on EmpowerHer. The first month, a home cook in Mumbai ordered our ground turmeric and left a review saying it was the most fragrant she had ever tasted. That review brought forty more orders. We now sell directly to over 300 households, our price per kilogram has doubled, and we have stopped depending on that single trader. We have also started selling value-added blends — biryani masala, rasam powder, sambar masala — all ground fresh to order.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1596040033229-a9821ebd058d?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Annapurna Reddy', 'Guntur, Andhra Pradesh'),

('Crochet Brought Me Back to Life',
'I lost my job at the garment factory during the pandemic. With a disabled husband and two children in school, I sat in my one-room home not knowing where the next meal would come from. My mother had taught me crochet as a child but I had never taken it seriously. I started making small bags, table mats, and wall hangings — anything to keep my hands busy and my mind from despair. My neighbor saw my work and told me about EmpowerHer. The platform help me list my items properly with good photos taken on a friend''s phone. My first sale of ₹350 made me cry. Today, eight months later, I earn between ₹8,000 and ₹12,000 every month from crochet. I have taken up a bigger room, my children are still in school, and I have started teaching crochet to women in my building on weekends.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1612965607446-25e1332775ae?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Fatima Shaikh', 'Dharavi, Mumbai'),

('Embroidery That Tells Our Tribe''s Story',
'Phulkari embroidery has been our tribe''s language for centuries — each motif tells a story of harvest, marriage, birth, longing. When synthetic fabrics replaced handloom and machine embroidery flooded the market, our women stopped making Phulkari because it did not pay. I refused to let it end. I formed a small collective of seven elder women who still remembered the old patterns. EmpowerHer gave us visibility we had never imagined. A fashion designer in Delhi found us through the platform and commissioned thirty custom dupattas for her collection. The collaboration was featured in a magazine. Orders have not stopped since. We now have twenty-three women stitching full-time, earning dignified wages, and our daughters are proud to say their mothers are artisans.',
'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1610186594416-2c7c0131e35d?q=80&w=2574&auto=format&fit=crop',
'Gurpreet Kaur', 'Amritsar, Punjab');
